    "summary": "The Ethiopian famine of 1983 to 1985 killed approximately one million people and affected millions more in the Tigray and Wollo regions of northern Ethiopia. The famine resulted from a combination of drought, the disastrous agricultural policies of the Derg military government, and the ongoing civil war between the government and insurgent groups, which disrupted food production and distribution and in some instances was deliberately used to starve populations in rebel-held areas.\n\nThe famine gained international attention through television footage broadcast in October 1984 by BBC journalist Michael Buerk and photographer Mohamed Amin, which showed starving and dying Ethiopians in harrowing detail. The footage prompted an extraordinary international response. Irish musician Bob Geldof organized the Band Aid charity single 'Do They Know It's Christmas?' in November 1984, which raised millions of pounds, and followed it with the global Live Aid concert in July 1985, which raised over £150 million and mobilized a new era of celebrity-driven humanitarian fundraising.\n\nThe famine exposed the Derg government's failures and its deliberate obstruction of aid to rebel regions. It accelerated the decline of the Mengistu regime and contributed to the eventual triumph of insurgent forces in 1991. The global response to the Ethiopian famine transformed international humanitarian fundraising and public awareness of African poverty, though it also raised lasting debates about the effectiveness and potential harms of celebrity charity campaigns and international food aid.",
